WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:03.120
Hi, my name is Joe Cheng.

00:00:03.120 --> 00:00:04.720
I am the CTO of Posit,

00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:07.920
and I'm so pleased to be here speaking with you

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:10.600
at R Plus AI.

00:00:10.600 --> 00:00:14.280
Today, I'm gonna talk about how we can take LLMs

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:18.719
and really focus them for working with data science

00:00:18.719 --> 00:00:22.299
and research in a way that is useful and responsible.

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:25.559
And when I'm talking about LLMs today,

00:00:25.559 --> 00:00:28.400
I'm really not talking about ChatGBT,

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:30.120
and I'm not talking about Copilot

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:32.320
or any kind of coding agent.

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:33.799
These tools are very useful,

00:00:33.799 --> 00:00:37.480
but I think we're all sort of accustomed to them.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:39.560
We're used to their trade-offs.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:42.880
And I think that one of the most interesting ways

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:44.439
we can think of LLMs today

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:47.080
is how to harness them as custom agents,

00:00:47.080 --> 00:00:51.560
how we take this sort of underlying ability that LLMs have

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:55.040
and use them to our own ends in our own custom workflows.

00:00:56.040 --> 00:00:58.560
And to that end, we've really tried to make it

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:03.279
as easy as possible for anyone with a background in R

00:01:03.279 --> 00:01:08.279
to be able to harness these LLMs for their own purposes.

00:01:08.599 --> 00:01:10.480
We have this package called Elmer

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:13.959
that I think is a really beautiful and elegant package,

00:01:13.959 --> 00:01:17.160
and it is one of my favorite packages

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:18.559
that we've released in recent years.

00:01:18.559 --> 00:01:20.040
And it just gives you the ability

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:24.080
to so easily tap into the power that LLMs have,

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:26.800
not just simple chat, as you can see here,

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:28.879
but the ability to do tool calling,

00:01:28.879 --> 00:01:30.440
to create agentic workflows,

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:33.000
and to create user interfaces on top of LLMs.

00:01:34.199 --> 00:01:37.800
Now, I'm not gonna get too far into Elmer today,

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:39.559
but I'd like you to take my word for it

00:01:39.559 --> 00:01:43.199
that if you are here and you know how to write R code,

00:01:43.199 --> 00:01:45.559
that you are ready to harness LLMs

00:01:45.559 --> 00:01:48.040
to create advanced agents.

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:52.000
It really is quite easy to get started with these things.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.360
So if we all have the ability to do this,

00:01:57.360 --> 00:01:59.559
that doesn't answer the question of whether we should,

00:01:59.559 --> 00:02:01.199
whether it's a good idea.

00:02:01.199 --> 00:02:04.400
And this is a question that is very near and dear

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:06.879
to my heart and to the heart of Posit,

00:02:06.879 --> 00:02:08.479
and to talk about why,

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:11.440
I wanna talk a little bit about where Posit comes from.

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:14.119
So we are a public benefit corp,

00:02:14.119 --> 00:02:16.320
and if you are not familiar with that concept,

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:18.720
you can sort of think of it as being a compromise

00:02:18.919 --> 00:02:23.160
between a for-profit company and a nonprofit organization.

00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:28.000
So we have all of the flexibility of a for-profit company,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.919
but we are motivated by a mission.

00:02:32.919 --> 00:02:37.559
And as a PBC, we have to state out loud what that mission is.

00:02:37.559 --> 00:02:39.800
And for us, this is sort of an abridged version

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:42.759
of the beginning of our official mission.

00:02:42.759 --> 00:02:44.600
Our mission is to create open source software

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:46.720
for data science, scientific research,

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:48.440
and technical communication.

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:52.000
And I really wanna focus on this data science

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.160
and scientific research.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:58.039
A lot of the use cases that are really important to us

00:02:58.039 --> 00:03:00.360
are things like people doing academic

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:02.279
and scientific research,

00:03:02.279 --> 00:03:05.600
people who are really using this stuff

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:09.399
for high stakes kinds of scenarios,

00:03:09.399 --> 00:03:12.559
people who are analyzing healthcare data,

00:03:12.559 --> 00:03:17.559
or doing drug development, deciding public policy,

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:21.279
environmental studies, epidemiology,

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:22.839
things that it's really important

00:03:22.839 --> 00:03:24.360
that your answers are correct

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:26.039
or people could really get hurt.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:28.440
And to kind of hammer this home,

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:31.080
I wanna point out this passage from a book called

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:35.039
Software for Data Analysis by John Chambers,

00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:38.160
who is the creator of S, the precursor of R.

00:03:39.679 --> 00:03:41.320
And Chambers makes this point.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:43.759
He says, those who receive the results

00:03:43.759 --> 00:03:46.800
of modern data analysis have limited opportunity

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:50.160
to verify the results by direct observation.

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:52.800
Users of the analysis have no option

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:54.839
but to trust the analysis and by extension,

00:03:54.839 --> 00:03:56.399
the software that produced it.

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:01.520
Both the data analysts, that's probably most of you,

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:04.440
and the software provider, that's us

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:06.800
and people who write packages for R,

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:08.919
therefore have a strong responsibility

00:04:08.919 --> 00:04:11.199
to produce a result that is trustworthy

00:04:11.199 --> 00:04:15.800
and if possible, one that can be shown to be trustworthy.

00:04:15.839 --> 00:04:18.839
This obligation I label the prime directive.

00:04:18.839 --> 00:04:22.760
So that's how seriously John Chambers takes it

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:25.799
and we've adopted this prime directive as our own

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:28.359
from the earliest days of the company.

00:04:28.359 --> 00:04:31.399
And one of our software engineers on the tidy models

00:04:31.399 --> 00:04:33.880
seem really hammer this home by saying,

00:04:33.880 --> 00:04:36.040
I'm aware that if I make a mistake,

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:39.959
bad things happen, death and other things.

00:04:41.399 --> 00:04:44.239
So if we have this principle in mind

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:47.799
and for us, it really is, it's more than a best practice.

00:04:47.799 --> 00:04:50.200
It's really a moral and ethical obligation

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:52.359
to adhere to this prime directive.

00:04:52.359 --> 00:04:53.839
What does that mean concretely?

00:04:53.839 --> 00:04:57.000
Like how does that translate into real concerns

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.720
as we work with data science software?

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:04.119
So number one, correctness is obviously paramount

00:05:04.119 --> 00:05:05.079
at all times.

00:05:05.079 --> 00:05:07.440
We wanna do our best to write software without bugs,

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:10.640
especially in the code paths that produce answers.

00:05:11.519 --> 00:05:13.679
Secondly, transparency.

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:16.239
We want the methods of our analysis

00:05:16.239 --> 00:05:18.440
to be able to be inspected

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:22.679
and having open source code goes a long way

00:05:22.679 --> 00:05:24.519
towards those ends.

00:05:24.519 --> 00:05:26.920
And third, reproducibility.

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:29.160
The ability for the analysis to be repeated

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:30.880
on the same data in the future,

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:33.320
hopefully producing the same results.

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:35.359
So these three principles of correctness,

00:05:35.359 --> 00:05:37.839
transparency and reproducibility

00:05:37.839 --> 00:05:39.799
are first and foremost in our minds

00:05:39.799 --> 00:05:43.880
any time we are working on a new tool

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:45.880
for helping with data analysis.

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:50.559
And when we hold these three principles against LLMs,

00:05:51.559 --> 00:05:53.720
this is not an obvious fit.

00:05:53.720 --> 00:05:56.959
Like it's actually quite an obvious misfit

00:05:56.959 --> 00:05:58.440
because when it comes to correctness,

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:02.559
LLMs are infamous for giving convincing but wrong answers.

00:06:02.559 --> 00:06:04.640
They're getting better all the time,

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:07.720
but this phenomenon of very convincingly telling you

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:12.720
the wrong thing is certainly still very prevalent.

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:14.679
Secondly, transparency.

00:06:14.679 --> 00:06:17.480
I mean, LLMs are the ultimate black box.

00:06:17.480 --> 00:06:20.119
We don't really understand what they do.

00:06:20.119 --> 00:06:22.239
We don't really understand how they do it.

00:06:22.239 --> 00:06:25.000
And in fact, the more you understand about them,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:29.040
the less what they are already capable of seems possible.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:33.440
And then finally, they are kind of inherently

00:06:34.399 --> 00:06:35.399
not reproducible.

00:06:35.399 --> 00:06:37.720
They're inherently non-deterministic

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:40.799
just by virtue of the way that they work.

00:06:40.799 --> 00:06:43.839
Some of the model providers will give you the ability

00:06:43.839 --> 00:06:47.399
to set a random seed, and even they will warn you

00:06:47.399 --> 00:06:49.399
that this is not fully reproducible

00:06:49.399 --> 00:06:51.559
because the answers will still vary

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:53.000
based on the underlying hardware

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:54.920
or their software configuration.

00:06:54.920 --> 00:06:57.000
So we inherently do not have the ability

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.760
to reproduce conversations or actions that LLMs take.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:05.480
And we've all seen this in action.

00:07:05.480 --> 00:07:08.799
Like, we've all asked LLMs things like,

00:07:08.799 --> 00:07:11.519
draw an intricate piece of ASCII art,

00:07:11.519 --> 00:07:13.799
and it says, here's an intricate piece of ASCII art

00:07:13.799 --> 00:07:15.679
of a wolf, penguin.

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:19.679
I mean, and it's very confidently saying,

00:07:19.679 --> 00:07:21.519
I've done this for you.

00:07:21.519 --> 00:07:23.600
Why does it do that?

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:24.720
We don't really know.

00:07:26.399 --> 00:07:28.720
And I wanna make sure you understand that my point here

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:32.320
is not that LLMs are bad or that they can't do things.

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:33.679
They can do a lot of things.

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:36.200
And in fact, the shape of the things that they can

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:38.880
and can't do is quite surprising.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:41.399
I think you could intuitively imagine

00:07:41.399 --> 00:07:43.440
that LLMs work like this,

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:45.839
that there is a spectrum of tasks

00:07:45.839 --> 00:07:49.600
that they could possibly do that range from very easy,

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:53.920
according to some criteria or intuition, to very hard.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:57.480
And you would think that the easy tasks they excel at,

00:07:57.519 --> 00:08:00.000
and as these tasks get harder, they get worse and worse,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:01.040
which is what you see here,

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:04.359
kind of a smooth, relatively smooth capability curve.

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:07.720
And that is not the world that we live in.

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:12.720
Today's LLMs do not reflect this kind of behavior.

00:08:13.160 --> 00:08:15.880
In fact, it's more like this,

00:08:15.880 --> 00:08:20.119
where there are very easy tasks that they excel at

00:08:20.119 --> 00:08:22.760
and very easy tasks that they are terrible at

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:25.079
and very difficult tasks that they excel at

00:08:25.119 --> 00:08:27.640
and very difficult tasks that they're terrible at.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:30.920
And it is very, very difficult to intuit

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:35.159
without trying to know what category

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:37.679
or whether this will be inside or outside

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:39.119
of their capability curve

00:08:39.119 --> 00:08:41.640
when you're thinking of a new task.

00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:45.840
Just to take two examples, they're quite good at coding.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:48.320
And I think you would think, as a human,

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:50.559
that coding is a pretty hard thing to do.

00:08:50.559 --> 00:08:53.119
There's a lot of logic and reasoning.

00:08:53.119 --> 00:08:54.200
There's a lot of nuance.

00:08:54.239 --> 00:08:55.880
There's abstractions.

00:08:55.880 --> 00:08:58.760
There's a lot of context that you need to hold in your head.

00:08:59.679 --> 00:09:01.719
There's a lot of intent that needs to be inferred

00:09:01.719 --> 00:09:03.359
from reading code.

00:09:03.359 --> 00:09:06.919
And yet, these models are incredibly good at it.

00:09:06.919 --> 00:09:10.359
But at the same time, the very simplest data tasks,

00:09:10.359 --> 00:09:12.119
they are really surprisingly bad at.

00:09:12.119 --> 00:09:16.000
And let me just give you a quick demonstration of that.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:17.599
So I tried to think of,

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:22.080
what is the very easiest data operation that you could do?

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:24.679
And the one I thought of was length.

00:09:24.679 --> 00:09:27.799
Given an array of values, how long is the array?

00:09:27.799 --> 00:09:30.119
How many elements are in the array?

00:09:30.119 --> 00:09:34.359
So to do this in R, we create an array of length n.

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:38.479
These are random floating point values between zero and one.

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:44.520
And then we ask, in this case, gbt 4.1,

00:09:44.559 --> 00:09:46.479
we ask it, how long is this array?

00:09:46.479 --> 00:09:49.799
And then we pass it those random numbers

00:09:49.799 --> 00:09:51.599
encoded as a JSON array.

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:56.039
And if you pass it 10 values to its credit,

00:09:56.039 --> 00:09:58.080
it will get it correct.

00:09:58.080 --> 00:09:59.479
At 100, it gets it correct.

00:09:59.479 --> 00:10:02.239
And even 1,000, it gives the correct answer.

00:10:03.599 --> 00:10:06.119
But then at 10,000, it says 1,000.

00:10:06.119 --> 00:10:09.039
I mean, it's not even close.

00:10:09.039 --> 00:10:11.960
And even these are cherry-picked round numbers.

00:10:11.960 --> 00:10:14.039
They're just powers of 10.

00:10:14.039 --> 00:10:17.760
When I gave it 103 elements, it said there were 100.

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:20.400
So this is a pretty disappointing showing

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:23.840
that even such a fundamental operation as length,

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:26.880
these models are not reliable for.

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:29.200
In fairness, when I made this slide,

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:30.039
this was definitely true,

00:10:30.039 --> 00:10:33.000
and gbt 4.1 was state-of-the-art.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.320
With gbt 5, it takes a very long time,

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:38.799
but I have mostly seen it give correct answers,

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:40.679
and the same with opus 4.1.

00:10:40.679 --> 00:10:43.599
So the state-of-the-art is changing,

00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:45.799
but the fact remains that an operation

00:10:45.799 --> 00:10:49.960
that feels like it should be simple and fundamental,

00:10:50.479 --> 00:10:52.400
we cannot trust these LLMs.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:54.479
And that does not bode well

00:10:54.479 --> 00:10:58.440
for all the other possible data science operations,

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:00.479
the fundamental operations you'd wanna do.

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:04.599
So given these inherent challenges,

00:11:04.599 --> 00:11:06.640
these challenges around correctness,

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:08.359
transparency, reproducibility,

00:11:08.359 --> 00:11:10.799
are there responsible ways to use LLMs

00:11:10.799 --> 00:11:12.119
in the service of data science?

00:11:12.119 --> 00:11:14.119
Are there responsible ways that we can leverage

00:11:14.119 --> 00:11:16.239
these kind of magical new tools?

00:11:17.239 --> 00:11:20.200
So what I am gonna show you now

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:23.719
are three different approaches that we have taken.

00:11:23.719 --> 00:11:27.760
And I wanna emphasize that these are not what I consider,

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:29.080
like these are principles

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:30.919
that everybody should be abiding by.

00:11:30.919 --> 00:11:32.599
These are just experiments that we ran

00:11:32.599 --> 00:11:34.840
and approaches that we kind of observed

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:37.119
have worked more or less well

00:11:37.119 --> 00:11:39.520
for these different scenarios that we tried.

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:43.599
So this is all evolving very quickly.

00:11:43.599 --> 00:11:45.359
Every model behaves differently.

00:11:46.880 --> 00:11:48.000
So we are approaching this

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.479
with a spirit of experimentation and humility

00:11:51.479 --> 00:11:54.000
and openness for each generation of LLMs

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.840
to bring us a different set of opportunities.

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:57.599
And I highly encourage you

00:11:57.599 --> 00:12:00.159
to think of these approaches in that spirit.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:03.119
So the first approach I wanna talk about

00:12:03.119 --> 00:12:06.760
is to constrain these LLMs, okay?

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:10.159
And what that looks like is we identify some things

00:12:10.159 --> 00:12:12.359
that these LLMs can do,

00:12:12.359 --> 00:12:16.000
at least take a particular model that you're targeting.

00:12:16.719 --> 00:12:19.799
And we decide, based on our empirical experience,

00:12:19.799 --> 00:12:23.760
okay, this LLM is very, very good at this one task

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:25.880
or this one skill.

00:12:25.880 --> 00:12:30.039
It is firmly inside the jagged frontier of their capability.

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:34.799
Then in order to make this one skill more useful,

00:12:34.799 --> 00:12:36.760
we kind of augment the LLM

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:38.799
with other kinds of software we write,

00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:41.440
like deterministic software

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:44.000
that kind of leverage that LLM skill

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.479
and make it more useful.

00:12:46.719 --> 00:12:48.440
And then we instruct the LLM,

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:51.599
just stick to the task we are giving you,

00:12:51.599 --> 00:12:53.880
stick to doing this thing that we've decided

00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:55.359
that you're very good at.

00:12:55.359 --> 00:12:58.280
And resist the urge to add features

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:00.760
that would pull the LLM in directions

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:03.280
that it's still okay at,

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:06.679
but maybe not quite as solidly good at.

00:13:06.679 --> 00:13:09.239
So the example I have in mind for this

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:14.000
is to use an LLM to drive SQL, to drive a dashboard.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.440
Let me show you what that looks like.

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:18.039
So this is a Shiny dashboard.

00:13:18.039 --> 00:13:19.880
This is not an LLM-powered dashboard.

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:21.679
This is just a regular Shiny dashboard.

00:13:21.679 --> 00:13:25.020
This is actually one of the templates for Shiny for Python.

00:13:26.039 --> 00:13:28.520
And just like a typical Shiny application,

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:30.440
you can see that there are some reactive outputs,

00:13:30.440 --> 00:13:32.840
and then there are some inputs on the side.

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:34.039
You know, if this was a real dashboard,

00:13:34.039 --> 00:13:36.559
there would probably be a lot more inputs than this.

00:13:36.559 --> 00:13:38.320
But as you change these values,

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:42.799
you can see that the values on the right update, okay?

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:45.159
So we asked ourselves,

00:13:45.159 --> 00:13:49.559
could we leverage these LLM's abilities

00:13:49.559 --> 00:13:51.919
to write SQL very well,

00:13:51.919 --> 00:13:55.119
and use that to enhance our dashboard

00:13:55.119 --> 00:13:56.520
with more capabilities?

00:13:56.520 --> 00:14:00.159
So here we've replaced all the filters with a sidebar.

00:14:00.159 --> 00:14:03.320
This is now written in R with Elmer and ShinyChat.

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:06.119
And we can ask these filtering questions

00:14:06.119 --> 00:14:09.679
like show only male smokers who had dinner on Saturday.

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:14.320
And this request goes out to an LLM.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:18.719
The LLM comes back with a select statement.

00:14:18.719 --> 00:14:21.719
And that select statement is shown to the user

00:14:21.719 --> 00:14:23.840
in two places.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:26.719
And then that select statement is applied

00:14:26.719 --> 00:14:31.080
to a data source by Shiny using reactive code.

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:32.840
And everything that you see down here,

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:34.280
this code has not changed.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:37.200
It is the same reactive Shiny code.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:39.960
It's just keyed off of a different reactive data frame,

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:42.679
one that is driven by this SQL.

00:14:42.679 --> 00:14:46.119
This technique works with any SQL speaking database

00:14:46.119 --> 00:14:47.919
that you can get to from R.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:51.960
And what this means is that we do not have to worry

00:14:51.960 --> 00:14:54.479
about these values being hallucinated.

00:14:54.479 --> 00:14:56.640
We don't have to worry about this plot

00:14:56.640 --> 00:14:59.239
or this table of numbers being hallucinated.

00:14:59.239 --> 00:15:03.719
All we have to worry about is whether this SQL is correct.

00:15:03.719 --> 00:15:08.080
And if you are someone who speaks SQL fluently,

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:09.960
then great, that's a very easy task for you.

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:12.919
But even if this is something that you're handing off

00:15:12.919 --> 00:15:17.200
to say your boss who doesn't speak SQL as well,

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:19.320
there's a really good chance that they can either

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:24.080
sort of intuit by reading the SQL.

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:26.200
They can intuit whether it's right or wrong.

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:28.919
And at worst, they can take that SQL and bring it to you

00:15:28.919 --> 00:15:31.200
and ask you to verify it.

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:34.159
But importantly, modern LLMs are quite good

00:15:34.159 --> 00:15:36.840
at writing SQL, so it's very infrequent

00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:38.679
that they make mistakes here.

00:15:38.679 --> 00:15:41.679
And we can use this capability to achieve filtering

00:15:41.679 --> 00:15:43.440
that we could not do.

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:46.760
We could not do with traditional Shiny controls.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:49.719
This is a very easy thing to reproduce in normal Shiny,

00:15:49.719 --> 00:15:51.840
that select these three criteria,

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:55.320
but something as simple as invert this filter

00:15:55.320 --> 00:15:57.760
and saying the ones that we're showing now

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:00.000
make those the only ones we are not showing.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.960
That is not an easy thing to do with most dashboard UIs.

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:07.840
There's a lot more that I could show you with this,

00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:09.799
but in the interest of time, I want

00:16:09.799 --> 00:16:12.640
to move on to these other points.

00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:19.960
This approach, this LLM SQL dashboard approach

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:23.119
turns out to be incredibly, incredibly useful.

00:16:23.119 --> 00:16:28.760
And I want to use this illustration

00:16:28.760 --> 00:16:30.679
from Rick and Morty.

00:16:30.679 --> 00:16:32.919
If you haven't seen the show, there's this one scene

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:35.280
where Rick, who is a scientist, he's

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:36.640
tinkering at the breakfast table,

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:39.960
and he builds this little robot.

00:16:39.960 --> 00:16:41.679
And the robot wakes up, and it immediately

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:43.919
asks, what is my purpose?

00:16:43.919 --> 00:16:46.840
And instead of answering, Rick asks the robot

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:47.840
to pass the butter.

00:16:47.840 --> 00:16:53.679
And the robot brings the butter over, and Rick's very happy.

00:16:53.679 --> 00:16:55.559
And then other things happen in this scene.

00:16:55.559 --> 00:16:57.159
They're having conversation while the robot just

00:16:57.159 --> 00:16:57.799
waits there.

00:16:57.840 --> 00:17:00.039
And then when there's a pause, the robot

00:17:00.039 --> 00:17:02.719
says, what is my purpose?

00:17:02.719 --> 00:17:06.439
And Rick says, you pass butter.

00:17:06.439 --> 00:17:12.680
And this poor robot goes, oh my god.

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:16.479
And this is sort of how I think of this scenario, where

00:17:16.479 --> 00:17:19.719
you have this LLM that is good at a lot of things.

00:17:19.719 --> 00:17:21.719
It has this very general capability,

00:17:21.719 --> 00:17:24.359
this very general intelligence.

00:17:24.359 --> 00:17:26.959
And we are really saying, you pass butter.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.640
You do this one thing, you just write SQL,

00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:32.439
and we do not want you to do anything else.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:38.479
So this approach of massively constraining

00:17:38.479 --> 00:17:41.359
what the model can do, is this a responsible approach?

00:17:41.359 --> 00:17:43.959
So in this case, in terms of correctness,

00:17:43.959 --> 00:17:46.000
we are asking it to generate SQL,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.280
and it generally does that incredibly well.

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:52.239
Certainly, I would say, at a superhuman level

00:17:52.239 --> 00:17:55.359
compared to the median, or even well

00:17:55.359 --> 00:17:59.119
above median data analysts.

00:17:59.119 --> 00:18:02.599
In terms of transparency, all the analysis

00:18:02.599 --> 00:18:04.000
that you're seeing on the screen is

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:08.520
driven off of a SQL query that is very clearly displayed.

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:10.359
And in terms of reproducibility, the fact

00:18:10.359 --> 00:18:14.760
that you can take that SQL and apply it later on,

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:17.880
and get the same result as long as the data has not changed,

00:18:17.880 --> 00:18:20.040
I think that qualifies.

00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:22.920
So this approach, we were so happy with this sort of like,

00:18:22.920 --> 00:18:27.000
take a SQL chatbot and apply it to a shiny data dashboard.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.719
It's worked so well that we have created an open source

00:18:29.719 --> 00:18:31.760
package called QueryChat.

00:18:31.760 --> 00:18:34.439
If you have a dashboard that is primarily

00:18:34.439 --> 00:18:36.920
driven off of a single data frame,

00:18:36.920 --> 00:18:39.479
it's so easy to drop in QueryChat

00:18:39.479 --> 00:18:44.319
and recreate this experience for your data.

00:18:44.319 --> 00:18:49.719
So that's the first approach, this approach of constraining.

00:18:49.719 --> 00:18:51.520
The second approach that we're going to take

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:55.079
is to micromanage the model.

00:18:55.079 --> 00:18:58.319
And in this case, we are going to have an incredibly tight,

00:18:58.319 --> 00:19:00.760
very, very tight human AI feedback loop,

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:04.000
where we're asking it to do tiny steps that we are then

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.199
immediately judging to be right or wrong.

00:19:07.199 --> 00:19:08.959
Or if it's not a matter of right or wrong,

00:19:08.959 --> 00:19:11.719
just whether we like it or don't like the result.

00:19:11.719 --> 00:19:13.359
And then we can correct it immediately,

00:19:13.359 --> 00:19:17.680
and again, see the new result.

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:20.560
I think the idea here is that if we are micromanaging

00:19:20.599 --> 00:19:24.680
AI this closely, then mistakes are all but guaranteed

00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:25.959
to be caught right away.

00:19:25.959 --> 00:19:28.319
So even if what we're asking the model to do,

00:19:28.319 --> 00:19:33.040
it is not 100% at, it's only 85% at, that is fine.

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:36.439
That 15% of the time, we'll just notice, we'll correct it,

00:19:36.439 --> 00:19:39.520
we'll help it get to the right place.

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:41.239
So the example I want to use here

00:19:41.239 --> 00:19:45.880
is a tool that I vibe coded this week to tweak plots.

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:49.000
So believe it or not, everything I'm going to show you,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.280
this is a shiny app.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:55.280
And I think one realization that I've had using ChatGBT

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:59.160
over the last year is that I find using my voice

00:19:59.160 --> 00:20:02.160
to speak to an LLM to be incredibly helpful

00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:05.880
for reducing the friction of fast iteration

00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:07.839
or giving a lot of information to an LLM.

00:20:07.839 --> 00:20:10.439
So that's the approach that we're taking here.

00:20:10.439 --> 00:20:12.680
Instead of typing into a chat box,

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:15.800
instead of typing into an input box,

00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:17.599
what I would like to see happen,

00:20:17.599 --> 00:20:19.319
I'm going to use my voice and use that

00:20:19.319 --> 00:20:21.760
to shorten the feedback cycle here.

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:25.160
So I'm going to start by,

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:27.280
I'm going to press and hold space bar

00:20:27.280 --> 00:20:29.400
and that'll let me speak and then I'll let go

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:31.280
and that'll send my command.

00:20:32.719 --> 00:20:35.520
Let's create a plot of MT cards.

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:38.079
So I'm going to create a plot of MT cards.

00:20:38.079 --> 00:20:40.439
So I'm going to create a plot of MT cards.

00:20:40.439 --> 00:20:43.119
Let's create a plot of MT cars.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:53.839
Okay, great.

00:20:53.839 --> 00:20:56.920
So you can see here it did that, it did create a plot.

00:20:56.920 --> 00:20:59.680
That's fine, it even colored by cylinder, that's nice.

00:21:01.560 --> 00:21:04.040
Can you make the text significantly bigger

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:05.800
and move the legend to the bottom?

00:21:11.439 --> 00:21:16.439
Great, make the data points a little bit bigger as well.

00:21:27.520 --> 00:21:29.319
All right, let's see.

00:21:29.319 --> 00:21:32.319
I'd like to see these sort of groupings a little bit better.

00:21:32.319 --> 00:21:35.640
Can you add a cell above to calculate the convex halls

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:37.280
based on the cylinders?

00:21:40.439 --> 00:21:41.280
Okay.

00:21:50.760 --> 00:21:51.760
Oh, great, okay.

00:21:53.239 --> 00:21:54.199
That looks pretty good,

00:21:54.199 --> 00:21:56.880
but let's get rid of the border of the convex hall.

00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:58.000
Just use the fill.

00:22:07.719 --> 00:22:08.560
All right, great.

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:10.400
And finally, I'm kind of colorblind.

00:22:11.239 --> 00:22:12.920
I'm having trouble telling between these colors.

00:22:12.920 --> 00:22:15.920
Can you pick some more colorblind friendly colors?

00:22:26.680 --> 00:22:28.719
All right, great, I think that looks pretty good.

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:36.920
So you can see there that what we're doing

00:22:36.959 --> 00:22:38.959
is so inherently...

00:22:48.400 --> 00:22:50.319
So as you can see in this example,

00:22:50.319 --> 00:22:53.079
this feedback loop is so tight

00:22:53.079 --> 00:22:56.040
and I'm so on top of every little thing that it's doing

00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:59.479
that it's sort of hard for it to get too far off track.

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:03.719
And in terms of an illustration for this one,

00:23:03.719 --> 00:23:04.880
what this feels like,

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:07.119
this is maybe a slightly dark example,

00:23:07.119 --> 00:23:08.599
but I think of the movie Whiplash,

00:23:08.599 --> 00:23:11.520
this famous not quite my tempo scene.

00:23:11.520 --> 00:23:12.599
If you haven't seen it,

00:23:13.680 --> 00:23:15.839
J.K. Simmons plays this band director

00:23:15.839 --> 00:23:18.599
and he's extremely, extremely exacting.

00:23:18.599 --> 00:23:21.520
So they start playing and he says,

00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:23.599
the equivalent of let's plot MT cars

00:23:23.599 --> 00:23:24.839
and Miles Teller is the drummer

00:23:24.839 --> 00:23:27.280
and he's like, aha, I did this.

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:28.280
This is going great.

00:23:28.280 --> 00:23:29.959
And nope, not quite.

00:23:29.959 --> 00:23:33.400
The scatter plot points are a little small

00:23:33.400 --> 00:23:37.160
and okay, so he fixes that.

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:39.359
Not quite, the text annotations

00:23:39.359 --> 00:23:42.680
and I want the y-axis to start at zero

00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:45.439
and are you serious with this color palette?

00:23:46.359 --> 00:23:49.319
And this poor model is just doing its best

00:23:49.319 --> 00:23:51.280
to satisfy our every whim.

00:23:52.400 --> 00:23:54.920
So this idea of we're just so on top of it,

00:23:54.920 --> 00:23:57.319
we are just so exacting

00:23:57.319 --> 00:23:59.439
and examining every minute detail

00:23:59.439 --> 00:24:01.719
of what this model is creating.

00:24:01.719 --> 00:24:04.239
So is this approach responsible?

00:24:04.239 --> 00:24:05.680
Is this like plot tweaking tool

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:07.920
and having this tight feedback loop?

00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:09.079
So in practice,

00:24:09.079 --> 00:24:12.479
I do feel like it makes far fewer mistakes

00:24:12.479 --> 00:24:13.760
than a human does

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:17.119
and the kinds of mistakes that it makes

00:24:17.119 --> 00:24:18.680
are usually easy to catch.

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:23.520
For example, if it gets your factors,

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:27.599
it treats your factors as unordered instead of ordered.

00:24:27.599 --> 00:24:29.760
Usually that's something that you can just sort of see

00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:31.079
and deal with quickly.

00:24:32.280 --> 00:24:35.199
Of course, it depends on what you're doing with this bot

00:24:35.199 --> 00:24:36.680
but in the case of visualizations,

00:24:36.680 --> 00:24:38.800
I think it's pretty good.

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:41.040
In terms of transparency,

00:24:41.040 --> 00:24:43.719
the user is directing what's happening here

00:24:43.719 --> 00:24:45.880
and you can see the R code

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:48.319
that it's generating at all times

00:24:48.319 --> 00:24:50.520
and I think that's really important.

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:52.119
And finally, it's reproducible.

00:24:52.119 --> 00:24:55.839
So like the R code that you are creating

00:24:55.839 --> 00:24:59.439
is generally going to be able to be saved in a script

00:24:59.439 --> 00:25:00.959
and uploaded to Git

00:25:00.959 --> 00:25:03.959
and just all the normal ways our scripts are reproducible.

00:25:05.719 --> 00:25:08.280
So overall, I'd say like this feels

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:11.400
just relatively low stakes.

00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:13.839
We're working in such small steps

00:25:15.280 --> 00:25:17.199
but it also helps a lot that

00:25:17.199 --> 00:25:19.239
by focusing on data visualization

00:25:19.239 --> 00:25:21.719
that there's a lot of subjectivity here.

00:25:21.719 --> 00:25:24.520
It's really easy to judge the outcome.

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:29.319
So the third approach that I wanna talk about,

00:25:30.199 --> 00:25:32.400
the third and final approach is deferred review.

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:35.520
So the idea here is that we're gonna have

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:38.280
a similar approach to the last one

00:25:38.280 --> 00:25:40.319
but with like kind of a looser rein,

00:25:40.319 --> 00:25:42.199
like a looser leash.

00:25:42.199 --> 00:25:45.560
So we're gonna ask the AI to do things

00:25:45.560 --> 00:25:48.359
with slightly bigger steps

00:25:48.359 --> 00:25:50.800
for it to be taking bigger leaps without us

00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:52.479
but still not just like going off

00:25:52.479 --> 00:25:54.119
and doing stuff without us.

00:25:54.119 --> 00:25:56.719
So we're still there, we're aware of what it's doing,

00:25:56.719 --> 00:25:58.319
we're still kind of directing it,

00:25:58.359 --> 00:26:00.000
we're aware of what kinds of questions

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:01.000
that it wants to answer

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:04.160
and we are directing it on what kinds of things to do next

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:06.479
but we are not closely scrutinizing

00:26:06.479 --> 00:26:08.800
every single step in every line of code

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:11.400
that it's writing for errors and hallucinations.

00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:16.839
Obviously, it needs to be decent at whatever it's doing

00:26:18.160 --> 00:26:21.079
but we're not gonna go over the top in terms of reviewing.

00:26:21.079 --> 00:26:22.800
So what that means is we are gonna enjoy

00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:25.520
this like really fast movement upfront

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:27.640
because we're not stopping to scrutinize everything

00:26:27.959 --> 00:26:30.520
but we are piling up sort of a review debt

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:33.439
along the way that we will eventually come due.

00:26:35.560 --> 00:26:37.839
And that is usually at the latest

00:26:37.839 --> 00:26:39.000
before you ship your work,

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:40.000
before you take your work

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:41.479
and actually put it in front of people

00:26:41.479 --> 00:26:43.520
who might act on it

00:26:43.520 --> 00:26:48.400
or who might misinterpret it as fully vetted analysis,

00:26:48.400 --> 00:26:51.199
that is when you need to stop and carefully review.

00:26:51.199 --> 00:26:54.000
I think of this as being akin to working in Git,

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:55.160
having your own branch

00:26:55.199 --> 00:26:58.000
and you're kind of working through things

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:01.160
and you kind of clean it up and get it all ready

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:03.880
and have it reviewed before you merge

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:05.839
but you generally do that at the end.

00:27:05.839 --> 00:27:08.800
So the agent that I wanna show you for this is DataBot.

00:27:10.119 --> 00:27:15.119
DataBot is our exploratory data analysis agent

00:27:15.560 --> 00:27:18.680
that we released recently

00:27:18.680 --> 00:27:21.439
and I think it's just one of the most exciting pieces

00:27:21.439 --> 00:27:23.760
of software that I've ever worked on.

00:27:25.640 --> 00:27:27.119
If you have not seen DataBot,

00:27:27.119 --> 00:27:32.119
it is an extension for Positron exclusively right now.

00:27:32.439 --> 00:27:35.079
So you need a relatively recent version of Positron

00:27:35.079 --> 00:27:37.439
and then you can install DataBot

00:27:37.439 --> 00:27:40.319
by going to the extensions pane here.

00:27:40.319 --> 00:27:43.400
You will need an Anthropic API key

00:27:45.119 --> 00:27:48.680
or I think we can also use AWS Bedrock

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:51.359
and very shortly,

00:27:51.359 --> 00:27:53.800
you'll be able to connect to other LLMs as well.

00:27:55.160 --> 00:27:57.959
By the way, this is not currently available in RStudio

00:27:57.959 --> 00:28:00.479
but it or something much like it

00:28:00.479 --> 00:28:02.319
will be coming to RStudio very soon.

00:28:03.839 --> 00:28:06.400
So I have DataBot here

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:10.239
and you wanna start out in a project or a folder

00:28:10.239 --> 00:28:12.359
that you're ready to do some work.

00:28:12.359 --> 00:28:17.079
So maybe you brought some data into this folder.

00:28:17.079 --> 00:28:18.359
In this case, I have a CSV

00:28:18.359 --> 00:28:20.199
but we could connect to a database also

00:28:20.199 --> 00:28:24.520
or use Databricks or an S3 bucket or SAS data,

00:28:24.560 --> 00:28:26.199
just anything you can do in R.

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:30.640
And then I'm just gonna start asking it questions

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:32.839
and I can ask it relatively high level questions.

00:28:32.839 --> 00:28:37.760
I can say just like load the CSV data in this directory.

00:28:37.760 --> 00:28:40.599
And after I give it a command,

00:28:40.599 --> 00:28:45.160
it is going to usually either call some tools

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:47.839
or write some code to try to answer that question.

00:28:48.719 --> 00:28:50.319
And in this case, it's doing both.

00:28:50.319 --> 00:28:53.479
It is both looking at what files are available

00:28:53.479 --> 00:28:57.520
in this directory and then it is executing some R code.

00:28:57.520 --> 00:29:02.439
And very importantly, both the model and ourselves

00:29:02.439 --> 00:29:06.239
as the users, we can both see this information

00:29:06.239 --> 00:29:09.199
that's coming out of the R code.

00:29:09.199 --> 00:29:12.239
So it looks at what happened here.

00:29:12.239 --> 00:29:14.920
It's looking at the summary here

00:29:14.920 --> 00:29:17.239
and it comes to these conclusions

00:29:17.239 --> 00:29:18.680
about what kind of data is here.

00:29:18.680 --> 00:29:21.520
And this appears to be like weather data

00:29:21.520 --> 00:29:24.199
about various countries and their capitals, okay?

00:29:24.199 --> 00:29:26.520
60,000 rows and 22 columns.

00:29:27.520 --> 00:29:30.959
And then it stops and gives us four suggestions

00:29:30.959 --> 00:29:32.839
for how to proceed.

00:29:32.839 --> 00:29:35.319
And this is incredibly important.

00:29:35.319 --> 00:29:38.079
If you look at these suggestions,

00:29:38.079 --> 00:29:43.079
they're quite specific and sensitive to what just happened.

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:48.640
Like these are not just scripted or stock suggestions

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:52.640
like, do you wanna do some data quality checks?

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:54.800
Do you want to transform the data?

00:29:54.800 --> 00:29:56.599
Do you wanna visualize the data?

00:29:56.599 --> 00:29:59.520
It's asking like pretty specific questions here

00:29:59.520 --> 00:30:00.719
like create visualizations

00:30:00.719 --> 00:30:02.680
of temperature patterns over time.

00:30:03.880 --> 00:30:07.400
So every interaction you have with Data Bot

00:30:07.400 --> 00:30:08.359
is gonna be like this.

00:30:08.359 --> 00:30:11.079
You ask a question or give it an instruction.

00:30:11.079 --> 00:30:13.079
It will run some code.

00:30:13.079 --> 00:30:15.099
It'll look at the results.

00:30:15.140 --> 00:30:18.939
It will make some observations,

00:30:18.939 --> 00:30:21.420
make some suggestions and then stop.

00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:24.060
And it is very important that it stop

00:30:24.060 --> 00:30:26.819
and not just run off and just answer whatever questions

00:30:26.819 --> 00:30:29.500
it feels like leaving us behind.

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:31.979
Data Bot is carefully tuned to work in chunks

00:30:31.979 --> 00:30:35.060
that feel good to a human,

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:37.219
that are enough for us to feel like we're making progress,

00:30:37.219 --> 00:30:40.619
but also that we can sort of have a general handle

00:30:40.619 --> 00:30:42.020
of what it's doing and why.

00:30:42.939 --> 00:30:45.540
So now let's ask it like create a visualization

00:30:45.540 --> 00:30:47.699
of temperature patterns over time.

00:30:51.099 --> 00:30:52.939
It's looking at how many countries.

00:30:54.819 --> 00:30:59.339
And okay, so this is temperature patterns

00:30:59.339 --> 00:31:01.939
for all 252 countries.

00:31:01.939 --> 00:31:06.260
This is just data from September to October of this year.

00:31:06.260 --> 00:31:08.699
And then it's separating it out by continent.

00:31:09.699 --> 00:31:13.020
And as before, we can see these plots

00:31:13.020 --> 00:31:15.420
and the model can see the plot.

00:31:15.420 --> 00:31:19.260
And then it makes some conclusions about what it sees here.

00:31:23.380 --> 00:31:26.979
And now we've asked and answered a whole bunch of questions.

00:31:26.979 --> 00:31:29.339
Like we've really taken it down a number

00:31:29.339 --> 00:31:31.760
of different pathways and we've ended

00:31:31.760 --> 00:31:33.660
with a pretty interesting,

00:31:33.660 --> 00:31:35.660
they're pretty scrunched because of my screen resolution

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:38.619
here, this plot that I think is pretty interesting.

00:31:39.459 --> 00:31:40.900
And I really don't care about everything else.

00:31:40.900 --> 00:31:43.579
Like really, this is the conclusion

00:31:43.579 --> 00:31:47.339
that I would really like to draw attention to.

00:31:47.339 --> 00:31:51.819
So with data bot, I have the ability to tell it,

00:31:51.819 --> 00:31:53.400
okay, we've done all this stuff.

00:31:53.400 --> 00:31:55.420
You've written all this code, answered all these questions

00:31:55.420 --> 00:31:58.099
that most of which I don't care about anymore.

00:31:58.099 --> 00:31:59.979
Let's create a reproducible artifact

00:31:59.979 --> 00:32:01.640
just about the thing that I do care about.

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:03.699
So I'll say like slash report to say,

00:32:03.699 --> 00:32:05.219
I wanna make a quarter report.

00:32:08.619 --> 00:32:09.459
Okay.

00:32:18.859 --> 00:32:20.979
So what this is gonna do is create

00:32:20.979 --> 00:32:25.520
a reproducible quarto document that takes what it's learned

00:32:25.520 --> 00:32:27.260
during the course of this conversation

00:32:27.260 --> 00:32:29.780
and makes a reproducible version.

00:32:32.060 --> 00:32:34.619
Okay, so you can see here that it created this report

00:32:34.660 --> 00:32:39.599
for us and reproduced this very nice visualization.

00:32:41.540 --> 00:32:45.619
And we also automatically drop this warning at the top.

00:32:45.619 --> 00:32:50.619
So this is your cue to carefully review each piece of code

00:32:51.219 --> 00:32:55.380
and each conclusion that is found in this report.

00:32:55.380 --> 00:32:58.359
And then you can remove that little disclaimer.

00:32:59.459 --> 00:33:02.939
So is data bot and this approach of deferred review,

00:33:02.939 --> 00:33:04.219
is it responsible?

00:33:05.380 --> 00:33:08.260
It is responsible in terms of correctness

00:33:08.260 --> 00:33:11.599
to the degree that you have the discipline and expertise

00:33:11.599 --> 00:33:16.020
to actually go back and review the work created by the model.

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:20.459
In terms of transparency, I mean, there is R code.

00:33:20.459 --> 00:33:24.520
It is telling you how it's coming to these conclusions.

00:33:25.660 --> 00:33:27.140
But I mean, to be honest,

00:33:27.140 --> 00:33:30.819
while you're in the thick of the exploration,

00:33:30.819 --> 00:33:32.140
there's a lot of R code coming at you

00:33:32.140 --> 00:33:33.640
and it's going by pretty fast.

00:33:34.699 --> 00:33:37.020
In terms of reproducibility, I think pretty good.

00:33:37.020 --> 00:33:39.819
This capability to generate a reproducible report for you,

00:33:39.819 --> 00:33:41.839
I think is incredibly important.

00:33:43.300 --> 00:33:46.579
So overall, compared to the other approaches,

00:33:46.579 --> 00:33:48.339
this is definitely riskier.

00:33:48.339 --> 00:33:51.739
But I will say it is so unbelievably useful

00:33:51.739 --> 00:33:56.660
that I certainly will not be doing exploratory data analysis

00:33:56.660 --> 00:34:00.479
without data bot or something like data bot in the future.

00:34:03.140 --> 00:34:06.099
So this plot is showing that for each approach

00:34:06.099 --> 00:34:07.020
that I've shown today,

00:34:07.020 --> 00:34:09.979
along with ChatGPT's deep research mode,

00:34:09.979 --> 00:34:13.419
what are the likelihoods that I think these approaches

00:34:13.419 --> 00:34:16.540
are likely to make a mistake from the model?

00:34:16.540 --> 00:34:20.040
And then on the y-axis, how likely is it

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:23.320
that that mistake would be overlooked by a human operator?

00:34:24.739 --> 00:34:29.419
And based on these different points in space,

00:34:29.419 --> 00:34:32.260
you have to decide what makes sense for you.

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:35.739
Where is your line in terms of what is responsible use

00:34:35.739 --> 00:34:38.780
of LLMs and what is not?

00:34:38.780 --> 00:34:43.159
So for example, if you work in marketing

00:34:43.159 --> 00:34:46.280
and you are trying to optimize the click-through rates

00:34:46.280 --> 00:34:48.219
of your mobile ads,

00:34:48.219 --> 00:34:50.820
then maybe you would draw the line somewhere here

00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:54.979
and anything below and to the left of the line

00:34:54.979 --> 00:34:57.560
is acceptable risk for you.

00:34:57.560 --> 00:35:01.500
But maybe you work in some field where lives are at stake.

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:05.699
Maybe you're working on nuclear power plant safety

00:35:05.699 --> 00:35:08.439
or drug development.

00:35:08.439 --> 00:35:10.919
Maybe in some of those cases,

00:35:10.919 --> 00:35:13.000
your tolerance is gonna be way down here,

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:15.840
that none of today's tools might be good enough

00:35:15.840 --> 00:35:16.919
for what you need.

00:35:18.959 --> 00:35:22.320
Or on the other hand, you might be an AI influencer

00:35:22.320 --> 00:35:25.840
on LinkedIn and then your tolerance is way out here.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:31.840
So that is what I have for you today.

00:35:31.840 --> 00:35:33.800
Thank you so much for your time and attention.

00:35:33.800 --> 00:35:36.760
And I'd be happy to take questions if there's time.

00:35:36.760 --> 00:35:37.600
Thank you.

00:35:44.439 --> 00:35:45.280
Amazing.

00:35:45.280 --> 00:35:49.520
Thank you, Joe, for putting together this talk

00:35:49.520 --> 00:35:53.479
and thank you everyone else for being with us today.

00:35:54.479 --> 00:35:58.600
We do have questions in the Q&A.

00:35:58.600 --> 00:36:02.080
I'm sure you can see everything.

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:05.199
So why don't we just go ahead

00:36:05.199 --> 00:36:09.320
and have you answer at your leisure.

00:36:09.320 --> 00:36:12.679
And we have until 45 minutes after the hour,

00:36:12.679 --> 00:36:15.360
so about eight minutes.

00:36:15.360 --> 00:36:16.639
So let's go.

00:36:16.639 --> 00:36:19.040
Oh, there are questions showing up here.

00:36:19.040 --> 00:36:19.879
Okay.

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:23.719
Yeah, so let me first address,

00:36:23.719 --> 00:36:25.360
first of all, thank you for having me

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:28.360
and thank you for your time and attention.

00:36:28.360 --> 00:36:33.360
Let me first address the local LLM question.

00:36:34.239 --> 00:36:38.479
So as we were developing this,

00:36:38.479 --> 00:36:41.520
as we were developing DataBot specifically,

00:36:41.520 --> 00:36:44.800
DataBot really emerged from specifically

00:36:44.800 --> 00:36:49.800
Claude Sonnet's ability to not only answer questions

00:36:49.879 --> 00:36:50.800
or your data questions,

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:52.439
but to be incredibly,

00:36:54.399 --> 00:36:56.959
like just really sensitive

00:36:56.959 --> 00:36:59.800
about what would make sense to do next.

00:37:00.679 --> 00:37:04.760
And what we found is that using other models at the time,

00:37:04.760 --> 00:37:07.239
really, even the frontier models

00:37:07.239 --> 00:37:10.199
from other proprietary labs,

00:37:11.159 --> 00:37:13.719
it fell off to the point that it really,

00:37:13.719 --> 00:37:16.520
to me, it didn't make sense to use this tool

00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:18.159
with another model.

00:37:18.320 --> 00:37:20.959
I do think that that situation has changed

00:37:20.959 --> 00:37:22.399
over the last few months.

00:37:22.399 --> 00:37:26.120
And what we have seen is that the best,

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:31.520
certainly GBT-5 can do a pretty decent job,

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:35.080
albeit it seems to require a lot more thinking,

00:37:35.080 --> 00:37:39.399
a lot more runtime token usage in order to do that.

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:44.959
But I think it seems very promising

00:37:44.959 --> 00:37:47.040
that we should be able to make it work well

00:37:47.040 --> 00:37:49.000
with things besides Claude.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:52.080
With local models, they have gotten a lot better

00:37:52.080 --> 00:37:55.040
over the last few months,

00:37:55.040 --> 00:37:56.600
or at least earlier this year,

00:37:56.600 --> 00:37:58.959
they seem to take a big leap forward.

00:37:58.959 --> 00:38:01.239
I'm still a little bit,

00:38:02.959 --> 00:38:04.840
I'm still waiting to see them get better still,

00:38:04.840 --> 00:38:08.199
I think before we can in good conscience recommend them.

00:38:08.199 --> 00:38:11.679
That said, for Positron in particular,

00:38:11.679 --> 00:38:16.679
we have the ability to connect to any OpenAI API

00:38:17.520 --> 00:38:19.360
compatible endpoint,

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:23.000
which I think somebody asked about,

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:24.639
like, do you have the ability to connect

00:38:24.639 --> 00:38:27.360
to your organization's local LLMs?

00:38:27.360 --> 00:38:31.040
So we can now say, yes, if it hasn't shipped already,

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:32.600
it will be shipping shortly.

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:33.840
I think it's already shipped

00:38:33.840 --> 00:38:35.360
for the desktop versions of Positron

00:38:35.360 --> 00:38:38.399
and should be coming out for Workbench shortly.

00:38:38.399 --> 00:38:40.879
And maybe it's something you have to search

00:38:40.879 --> 00:38:42.159
for how to enable it.

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:45.719
So I think this does give you the ability

00:38:45.760 --> 00:38:49.159
to connect to a lot of different kinds of models.

00:38:49.159 --> 00:38:52.840
But I continue to think that today,

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:55.159
you're not likely to have an awesome experience

00:38:55.159 --> 00:38:58.879
unless you're connecting to one of the Cloud models.

00:38:58.879 --> 00:39:01.439
Actually, Cloud SONNET or Cloud HYCU

00:39:01.439 --> 00:39:03.719
are both really excellent.

00:39:03.719 --> 00:39:07.840
And I think partially for these kinds of advanced agents,

00:39:07.840 --> 00:39:10.879
there's more tailoring to a specific model

00:39:10.879 --> 00:39:12.360
than you would think.

00:39:12.360 --> 00:39:13.399
A lot of what we do,

00:39:13.399 --> 00:39:15.639
like it's almost like we're trying to fit

00:39:16.560 --> 00:39:19.520
a custom suit onto this body.

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:20.959
And then everybody's asking,

00:39:20.959 --> 00:39:23.840
can I just swap this out for a totally different body?

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:25.520
And it's really difficult

00:39:25.520 --> 00:39:28.360
because we have so carefully measured

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:29.439
and tweaked and tucked

00:39:29.439 --> 00:39:32.000
so that it fits just well with this model.

00:39:33.199 --> 00:39:36.159
So I can't really guarantee that you'll get good results

00:39:36.159 --> 00:39:37.600
if you use it with something else.

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:40.280
I'll also say that as this moves to RStudio,

00:39:41.439 --> 00:39:44.520
we are re-examining some of these assumptions

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:46.840
and even our business model of like,

00:39:46.840 --> 00:39:50.320
how does this fit into our larger business?

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:54.199
So, part of what we would like to be able to do

00:39:54.199 --> 00:39:59.199
is to have you get your AI token generators from us

00:40:01.840 --> 00:40:03.439
and not have to worry too much

00:40:03.439 --> 00:40:06.840
about what exact model is behind the scenes.

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:09.919
Granted, that'll be a big problem for a lot of companies.

00:40:09.919 --> 00:40:13.439
One more, just to say one more thing about this topic

00:40:13.439 --> 00:40:16.399
and then I'll move on to the other questions.

00:40:16.399 --> 00:40:18.800
A lot of people have said to me,

00:40:18.800 --> 00:40:23.800
my company doesn't let me use anything but local LLMs.

00:40:24.679 --> 00:40:27.080
That was much more true a year ago than it is today.

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:30.040
I think in the time since people have realized,

00:40:30.040 --> 00:40:33.120
even your IT security people have realized,

00:40:33.120 --> 00:40:37.479
we cannot deprive ourselves of these proprietary models,

00:40:37.479 --> 00:40:39.520
even if we have to be HIPAA compliant,

00:40:39.520 --> 00:40:41.520
even if we're dealing with sensitive data.

00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:45.760
So, all the cloud providers now have LLMs

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:47.560
that are zero data retention.

00:40:47.560 --> 00:40:51.560
They don't train, they don't learn about your topic.

00:40:51.560 --> 00:40:55.120
They're just completely, they have the same data guarantees

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:57.800
as anything else running on AWS or on Azure.

00:40:57.800 --> 00:40:59.719
Microsoft has had that all along.

00:40:59.719 --> 00:41:01.199
Yes, yeah.

00:41:01.199 --> 00:41:02.879
So, I think all these cloud providers

00:41:02.879 --> 00:41:03.919
have had that all along,

00:41:03.919 --> 00:41:05.959
but what has changed over the last year

00:41:05.959 --> 00:41:07.679
is that a lot of companies have realized that.

00:41:07.679 --> 00:41:10.320
So, instead of insisting on local models,

00:41:10.320 --> 00:41:13.199
they are telling their employees like Bedrock is fine,

00:41:13.199 --> 00:41:17.040
Azure AI is fine, Vertex APIs are fine.

00:41:18.399 --> 00:41:20.360
Okay, I hope that helps.

00:41:21.280 --> 00:41:24.000
Okay, so Paul in Chicago asks,

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:25.199
aside from pure data science,

00:41:25.199 --> 00:41:27.600
I'm wondering how Joe uses AI in his software engineering,

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:30.840
if at all, seeing his examples would be highly instructive.

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:32.439
Absolutely.

00:41:32.439 --> 00:41:35.040
I was very resistant to this at first.

00:41:36.159 --> 00:41:37.520
Well, not resistant to trying it,

00:41:37.520 --> 00:41:40.199
but like I definitely was rooting against these tools,

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:43.560
partially because I've spent almost 30 years as a programmer

00:41:43.560 --> 00:41:45.000
and it's a big part of my identity

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:47.120
and I really love programming

00:41:47.120 --> 00:41:49.120
and it makes me feel smart and special.

00:41:49.120 --> 00:41:52.040
And for that to be kind of outsourced to a machine

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:53.199
super bums me out.

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:56.439
That being said, the tools have gotten better and better.

00:41:56.439 --> 00:41:57.479
I use them all the time.

00:41:57.479 --> 00:41:58.840
And I think these days,

00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:01.879
I will probably 50% of the time

00:42:01.879 --> 00:42:03.560
try something with cloud code first

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:05.560
and 50% of the time just start typing.

00:42:06.479 --> 00:42:08.399
And I'm trying to increase the amount of time

00:42:08.399 --> 00:42:09.679
that I turn to cloud code first,

00:42:09.679 --> 00:42:10.719
because it really is.

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:14.120
That second demo, the voice one,

00:42:14.120 --> 00:42:16.679
was entirely written by cloud code.

00:42:16.679 --> 00:42:18.199
I mean, I had to be there.

00:42:18.199 --> 00:42:19.959
There were a lot of things that it wanted to do

00:42:19.959 --> 00:42:21.679
that I had to steer it back into the right direction,

00:42:21.679 --> 00:42:23.760
but I did not write a single line of that code.

00:42:23.760 --> 00:42:25.320
And that was like a shiny app

00:42:25.320 --> 00:42:27.120
and looked nothing like a shiny app.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:31.719
It had all of the Jupyter Notebook keyboard shortcuts.

00:42:31.719 --> 00:42:33.760
And I mean, it was just astonishing

00:42:33.760 --> 00:42:36.080
what they're able to do today.

00:42:36.080 --> 00:42:37.399
So I highly encourage you,

00:42:37.399 --> 00:42:39.000
if you can't get access to some of these

00:42:39.199 --> 00:42:41.360
agentic coding tools at work,

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:45.520
then it's worth it to play with them on your own time.

00:42:45.520 --> 00:42:49.479
Just this is the future.

00:42:49.479 --> 00:42:51.760
At least human plus AI is the future.

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:53.760
I really hope that it stops there

00:42:53.760 --> 00:42:55.919
and doesn't just become like AIs are just the future

00:42:55.919 --> 00:42:57.639
and we don't do any more coding,

